# Process Management in Linux

Process management handles running programs, CPU usage, memory usage, background jobs, and service control.  
This document explains **what process management is**, **what it manages**, and **the essential commands**.

---

## 1. Management Area: Process Management

---

## 2. Definition – What Process Management Manages

Process Management handles:

- Monitoring running processes  
- Killing or stopping processes  
- Adjusting CPU priority  
- Running tasks in background or foreground  
- Managing daemons and services  

It ensures stable, efficient system operation.

---

## 3. Commands List

---

### View Processes

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `ps aux` | Show all processes |
| `ps -u username` | Show user processes |
| `pgrep name` | Find PID by name |
| `pidof process` | Get PID |

---

### Kill or Control Processes

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `kill PID` | Stop a process |
| `kill -9 PID` | Force kill process |
| `pkill name` | Kill by name |
| `kill -STOP PID` | Pause process |
| `kill -CONT PID` | Resume process |

---

### Process Priority

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `nice -n value command` | Run with priority |
| `renice -n value -p PID` | Change running process priority |

---

### Background & Foreground Jobs

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `command &` | Run in background |
| `jobs` | Show background jobs |
| `fg %1` | Bring job to foreground |
| `bg %1` | Resume job in background |
| `Ctrl+Z` | Suspend a process |

---

### Monitoring Tools

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `top` | Real-time monitoring |
| `htop` | Advanced process viewer |

---

## Summary

- Process management controls running programs and system resources.  
- `ps`, `kill`, `top`, and `nice` are essential tools.  
- Background job control uses `fg`, `bg`, and `jobs`.

